Class SelectExpressionInterpreter

All Implemented Interfaces:
IExpressionInterpreter<SelectExpression>
public class SelectExpressionInterpreter
extends ExpressionInterpreterImpl<SelectExpression>

Special interpreter class to interpret select-expressions.

The grammar production rule of the expression is:

select-expression ::= SELECT < value-expression > [ FROM value-expression ] [ WHERE boolean-expression ] [ ORDER BY < value-expression > ] [ UNIQUE ] [ OFFSET value-expression ][ LIMIT value-expression ]

Author:
Sven Krosse

interpretFromClause

private QueryMatches interpretFromClause(ITMQLRuntime runtime,
                                         IContext context,
                                         java.lang.Object... optionalArguments)
                                  throws TMQLRuntimeException
Internal method to interpret the contained form-clause if exists. The from-clause define the context of variable bindings during the interpretation of the where-clause. Variables can only bind to values specified by the from-clause. If the from-clause is missing, the current topic map will use as context.

Parameters:
runtime - the TMQL4J runtime
context - the current querying context
optionalArguments - optional arguments
Returns:
a query match containing the results of the from-clause interpretation or null if from-clause is missing.
Throws:
TMQLRuntimeException - thrown if interpretation fails

interpretWhereClause

private QueryMatches interpretWhereClause(ITMQLRuntime runtime,
                                          IContext context,
                                          java.lang.Object... optionalArguments)
                                   throws TMQLRuntimeException
Internal method to interpret the internal where-clause if exists. The where-clause define the condition which shall be satisfied by the tuple of variable bindings. The where-clause bind variables to defined values which satisfies the contained expression, only these variables can be used in the select-clause.

Parameters:
runtime - the TMQL4J runtime
context - the current querying context
optionalArguments - optional arguments
Returns:
the results of the where-clause
Throws:
TMQLRuntimeException - thrown if interpretation fails
